The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 Chief minister Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee will inaugurate a 40 million-gallon water-treatment plant in Palta, on the northern fringes of the city, on Monday. The plant has been set up at a cost of Rs 19 crore.

 fter it is commissioned, the daily supply of potable water from Palta will be 260 million gallons. According to municipal commissioner Alapan Bandyopadhyay, the new plant will be the last major addition in terms of capacity to the Palta waterworks.

 Singapore Airlines has announced special fares for trips to Bali from Calcutta. The Unbelievable Bali offer is available for Rs 14,990 a passenger. The package includes airfare, three nights? stay and return airport transfers. Bookings must be made between February 3 and February 24, and will be valid for travel from Calcutta from February 3 to March 31.

 Burglars broke open the shutters of a cellphone shop on Mission Row, in Bowbazar, and decamped with 28 mobile handsets and Rs 50,000 late on Thursday. The theft was noticed by employees after the shop was opened around 8 am on Friday. The lock of the cash box was found broken. No one has been arrested. Police suspect the burglary was committed by the gang that had cleaned out a few shops in the city in the past few weeks.

 A 25-year-old man was crushed under the wheels of a private bus on Narkeldanga Main Road on Friday afternoon. Police said the mishap occurred around 1.50 pm, when the bus on route 235 hit the motorcycle Rajeev Ram was riding. As Ram fell on the road, the bus ran over him. The driver tried to flee, but local residents caught hold of him and handed him over to police. The bus has been impounded.

 Police are yet to find a clue to the fate of Salt Lake-based timber trader Raj Kumar Seksaria, who went missing on Monday. His family has not received any ransom call. Raj, 45, left his residence in DL Block on Monday afternoon. He reportedly visited a client in Topsia, who owed him money. A missing diary was lodged on Tuesday morning. 

 The Calcutta Municipal Corporation, in association with private parties, has taken up a pilot project on slum development. The authorities will soon invite expressions of interest from private parties for two slums in prime locations in the city. Both slums are on private plots.

 The civic parks and gardens wing has taken up a Rs 5-lakh scheme to revamp Jorabagan Park, in north Calcutta. Mayoral council member Faiyaz Ahmed Khan said a major part of the amount will be spent on beautifying the park and building a gymnasium. Local residents have alleged that the civic body had destroyed the greenery of the park to set up a water treatment plant and a booster station.

 A live ophthalmology surgical workshop on the treatment of hyperopia (plus power) and presbyopia (bifocal power) by Conductive Keratoplasty was held this week at Shree Netra Eye Foundation. Conductive Keratoplasty uses radio frequency energy and is bloodless. During the workshop, surgery was carried out on four patients and shown live on a screen.

 TO B.P. Poddar Clinic for organising a free gynaecological clinic every Tuesday between 11 am and 1 pm




